review_blob: Bottle. Pours clearly amber with beautfiul white head. Aroma of sweet fruits and caramel. Maybe with a little presence of alcohol. Powerful taste! Bittersweet, caramel, some dried fruits. Good. Actually, very good.

Bottle. Pours dark golden with nice white head. Aroma? Well used american hops. Citrus, reisin, fruits. It tastes like Double IPA should taste. Sweet and bitter with some fruity notes. Well-hidden alcohol. Very good.

Bottle. Pours almost black with some dirty-white head. Sweet aroma. There is a caramel, but theres also lack of promised coffee and chocolate. Same in taste. Its full-bodied and sweet, lack of roastiness, lack of bitterness. In blind test, I would have said strong sweet stout or something like that. Not my glass of beer.
Bottle. Pours dark brown with medium beige head. Milk chocolate in aroma. Same in taste with some sour-roasty notes. Smooth. Drinkable. Good.

Bottle. Pours orange, hazy as its real ale. Nice aroma, even when youre in love with American hops. Could be more intensive, though. Theres a good maltiness finishing with some bitterness. Typical English-fruity. Quite good.
Bottle. Pours orange, hazy, medium head. Aroma is not intensive. Some lemony citrus notes and well-hidden coriander. Same flavours woth some cereal notes. Average.
Bottle. Pours black with very nice "dirty" white head. Loads of coffee with some chocolate notes in aroma. Full-bodied, coffee, chocolate, some roasty notes, low carbonation. Great.

Bottle. Pours dark orange, very hazy, with huge white head. Overcarbonated, bretts have eaten something inside the bottle. Very good aroma. Fruity, floral. Its dry, with some bitterness, really fruity, with some funky notes. Good.
Bottle. Pours black with too big brown heaf. The beer is overcarbonated. Aroma of coffee, dark chocolate and caramel. Some sweetness, cocoa, bitter finish. Okay.

Bottle. Pours light golden, hazy, nice white head with some lacing. Very good aroma, mango, peach, nectarine and so on. Good balance, very fruity, sweet but not too malty. Short, bitter finish. Well, very interesting, very good.

Bottle. Pours hazy, light yellow with white head which isnt very nice and disappears quickly. Very fresh aroma, citrus, maybe citric even, little bit spicy, maybe some leather notes. Very dry, refreshing with nice bitterness. Good.

Bottle. Pours dark golden, with nice white head. There are some hops in aroma, but its Imperial IPA, so you expect something more. And there is more in flavour. Bitterness is really high, which I actually love. But, if it is an Imperial, there should be more sweetness too. So, it tastes more like standard IPA. I mean, good IPA.

Bottle. Pours black with small beige head. Strong aroma of fresh roasted coffee and cocoa. Wow. Full-bodied but not sweet, loads of dark malts, coffee and dark chocolate, you know, 90% cocoa. Really nice, bitter, roasted aftertaste. Very good one.
beer_name: Brewfist / Prairie Artisan Ales Spaghetti Western

review_blob: Bottle. Pours dark red-amber with medium white head. Aroma of cookies, toffee, caramelized sugar. A little bit overcarbonated. Oh, the taste is definitely rich. Like a pie with loads of toffee. Some fruity and spicy notes too. Biscuity aftertaste. Good.

Bottle. Pours almost black, with nice beige head. Aroma isnt really intensive, some dark malt notes, I expected more coffee. It comes in taste, really nice coffee notes without some sourness which you could find in beer with coffee addition. Really nice, drinkable porter.

Bottle. Pours dark golden, clear, with nice white head. Aroma of hops, that for sure, some fruity-citrus-resin stuff, but definitely could be more intensive. Its quite dry, with some hoppy notes, drinkable. Average IPA,
Bottle. Pours golden, clear, with nice white head. Citrus! Loads of citrus!!! Dry, bitter, hoppy, citrus, grapefruit., Drinkable. GREAT IPA!

Bottle. Jet black, small beige head which disappeares completely. Pralines, cherry-liqour-chocolate. Sweet, chocolate, roastiness. Some warming alcohol and great lasting milk-vanilla-chocolate aftertaste. Impressing.

Bottle. Pours black with quite small head that doesnt last long. Dark chocolate, roastiness and whisky notes in nose. Full-bodied, chocolate, some coffee, good but balanced sweetness. A little bit of noble, warming alcohol. Very nice.
Bottle. Pours clear, dark golden, nice white head. There are 7 hops in aroma! Fruity, floral. Nice body, short but very good bitterness. Very easy-drinking. Its 8% ABV, so maybe too easy. Very good.

Bottle. Orange-golden, hazy, nice white head with good lacing. Hoppy aroma - some green notes, I would say. Good body - the main note in taste is malty sweetness which I actually dont really like but here its okay. Then comes the bitterness, its gentle, not brutal. There are hoppy flavours as well. I expected more offensive beer, but its a well-balanced, good IPA.
beer_name: Rogue Nation Brutal India Pale Ale

review_blob: Bottle. Pours hazy golden with medium white head. No lacing. Hoppy aroma. Equinox? Nice balance between sweetness from malt and bitterness. With some hoppy flavours could be even better. Still a good one.

Bottle. Pours clear golden with medium white head. Nice hoppy aroma, citrus, tropical fruits, maybe white fruits as well. Some kind of emptiness in taste... Bitterness isnt more as at medium level, its quite dry, theres also lack of hoppy notes. A little bit disappointed.
Bottle. Pours clear amber with nice, small head. Aroma is sweet, malty, dried fruits, toffee. Same in taste with kind bitterness. Pleasant alcohol warming. Good.

Bottle. Pours clear, fark golden, beautiful white head. Aroma is a.mixture of yeast and hops, maybe a little bit of bubble gum. Citrus and spicy. Taste come from maltiness, its also spicy, reisiny, citrusy. Pleasant bitterness. Warming finish. Very good.
Bottle. Pours hazy orange. Aroma - some canned fruits in sirup. Sweet with fruity notes and some bitterness. Decent.
Bottle. Pours dark golden with medium white head. Aroma and taste reminds me of multivitamin or tropical fruit juice. Bittersweet finish. Nice.

Bottle. Pours orange, hazy with huge white head. It looks like overcarbonated and it is indeed. Its a pity. Very nice, hoppy aroma, mostly tropical fruits. It tastes like good American Pale Ale, sweetness and hoppiness but its not really beer for a hophead - bitterness could be more intensive. Good one though, although its overcarbonated, what does disturb.
Bottle. Orange, hazy small white head. Aroma of melon with a hint of citrus. A little bit bland, fuzzy with some fruitness. Nothing special.
Bottle. Almost black, beige small head. Coffee and dark chocolate. Bitter enough. Drinkable. Good.

Bottle. Hazy, dark orange with some nice white head. Aroma of hops! Pineapple, apricot. But with some tine you give the beer to warm up, you can find notes tgat cone from old hops... They arent nice. Taste is bittersweet. Some decent hoppy character. Good one. Brewed with fresh hops would have been better.

Bottle. Pours almost clear, orange. Head disappeares quickly. Hoppy aroma - some woods, but it is not intensive. There is hop in taste, but also maltiness. Alcohol! It disturbes. Ok, its 8% ABV, but there are ways to hide it. Could be better.
Bottle. Not intensive hoppy aroma. Taste - theres some kind of hoppiness, but it all does not come together well. Bitterness is.medium, could be better. A little bit disappointed with this beer.
Bottle. Pours amber, small head. Aroma comes from malt and fermentation. Sweet abd fruity. Highly carbonated. Not my thing.

Bottle. Pours black with beige head, that stays nicely. Hoppy aroma! Really nice. In taste you gate coffee roastiness but a lot of hops too. They didnt forget about bitterness and Im really glad with that. Reallt good beer!
Bottle. Pours black with beige head, which disappeares quickly. Aroma of milk chocolate. Tastes sweet, with hints of chocolate. Full-bodied and maybe a little bit too much carbonation.

Bottle. Pours jetblack, with beautiful brown head. Aroma reninds of belgian chocolate. Some alcohol in the background, but in a noble way. Tastes really good. Sweetness, chocolate, bitterness and then roastiness, cocoa, some warming alcohol. Its smooth, even kinda easy-drinking, of course when youre aware that its still a RIS.

Bottle. Hazy, light golden. Big head with some lacing. Some citrus in aroma, also fruity notes from fermentation. Its easy drinking, fruity, hoppy notes in taste but bitterness is only at the medium level, which makes it more sweet, maybe too sweet, when it should be an IPA.
beer_name: Hffner Bru Hopfenstopfer Incredible Pale Ale

review_blob: If you read the label, youll know that its actually not a Witbier. No coriander, no orange peel, no unmalted wheat. But it looks like a witbier, its yellow, hazy with nice white head. Really nice aroma, with citrusy notes coming from some interesting hops. Its drinkable, refreshing, really good. Still, its not a Witbier. Who cares?
Bottle . Pours black, with almost white, nice head. Some chocolate in aroma. Taste reminds of sweet black coffee with caramel sirup, served chill.

Bottle. Pours orange, hazy. Quite big, nice white head. Fruity, hoppy notes in aroma with a little spicy disturbing something. Like that. Taste its quite sweet. Some hoppiness is there with the same notes from the aroma. Good one.

Bottle. Golden, clear, pours with medium white head that disappeares quickly. Hops in aroma, but its not a hop bomb. Taste is more sweet than bitter. There are a lot of malts in this beer but where are hops? It needs more bitterness. A little bit of alcohol in aftertaste.

Bottle. Orange, hazy, quite big white head. Grapes and apples in aroma, not really intensive. Sone citrus chsaracter in taste with nice malty sweetness and lack of IPA-like bitterness. Medium carbonation.
Bottle. Pours more red than brown. Nice white head. Malty aroma, maybe a little nutty note, but could be just a suggestion. Taste is also on malty way, some melanoidin is present too. Low carbonatedm
Bottle. Pours orange, hazy, unclear. Intensive hoppy aroma, fruits and raisin. Same in taste, its dry, hoppy, refreshing. Great everydays beer with 3,4% ABV.

Indeed golden, with not so beautiful white head. Smells typic belgian, a little bit peachy, spicy, with some notes of alcohol in the background. Quite highly carbonated, fruity, drinkable but nothing else. Good Belgian blond ale, thats what.
Bottle. Pours black, mwdium beige head. Chocolate. Loads of chocolate in aroma. Taste is impressive. Dark chocolate, milk chocolate, a little bit of roastiness too. Its very smooth and very good.
Bottle. Little gushing. Pours dark amber with huge head (too high carbonation). Sweet, fruity and spicy aroma. Taste is also sweet, red and dark fruits, quite balanced. Nice one.

Bottle. Golden with nice white head. Intensive (the beer is 13 months old!), typical for American hops, wonderful aroma. Full of malty sweetness, very fruity, loads of hops. Very short, noble bitterness. Very drinkable, you dont feel this 9,5% ABV at all. The great one.

Bottle. Pours orange-golden, a little bit hazy. Not so intensive aroma of citrus and tropical fruits. Taste is quite impresive, when you know that youre drinking a beer from a Bitburger Group. Nice malty sweetness, fruity notes and really good bitterness from American and German new-wave hops. With this taste and 6,4% ABV its a more than solid IPA; definitely better than I expected!
